                <h1>&#039;Happy Birthday, Frankenstein!&#039; celebrates the cinematic legacy of literature&#039;s favorite monster</h1>
                
                                    <figure class="dom-art-container my-4">
                                                    <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/e04707d9-0054-4a66-aa12-817f971a778c.sized-1000x1000.jpg?w=1000" alt="James&#x20;Whale&#x27;s&#x20;1931&#x20;film&#x20;&quot;Frankenstein&quot;&#x20;was&#x20;an&#x20;early&#x20;instance&#x20;of&#x20;Frankenstein&#x27;s&#x20;monster&#x20;in&#x20;film,&#x20;portrayed&#x20;here&#x20;by&#x20;Boris&#x20;Karloff." class="w-100">
                                                <div class="domphoto-caption mt-2 text-left text-md-right">
                            James Whale's 1931 film "Frankenstein" was an early instance of Frankenstein's monster in film, portrayed here by Boris Karloff.

                                                             <aside class="photo-caption photo-credit d-block pl-1">
                                    <figcaption class="d-block">
                                                                                    Photo by <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/courtesy-of-wikimedia-commons">Courtesy of Wikimedia Commons</a> |
                                                                                                                                The Chronicle
